Display the current directory location:
  pwd
Navigate to the "apt" directory:
  cd /etc/apt
List the current directory's files and permissions:
  ls -l
From the current location, use the proper command to list all files in the current user's home directory:
  ls /home/kali
Navigate back to the logged user's home directory:
  cd
Create a new dirctory:
  mkdir folder 1
  ls | grep folder1
Navigate to the newly created directory, and create four directories. "dir1" to "dir4"
  cd folder1
  mkdir dir{1..4}
Navigate to dir1, and then create three Parent/Child directories:
  cd dir1
  mkdir -p parent/child/grandson
  ls -R
Remove dir1 and dir2:
  rmdir dir{1..2} or rm -r dir{1..2}
Navigate to dir3, and create two text files using the appropriate command:
  cd dir3
  touch file{1..2}.txt or touch file1.txt file2.txt
Write "Hello" to file.txt
  echo "Hello" >> file.txt
Print the content of the file.txt
  cat file.txt
Copy and rename file.txt to file2.txt
  mv file.txt file2.txt
Edit the content using nano
  nano file.txt
Browse firefox and ping
  firefox & ping 8.8.8.8
Ping. If wrong format write "bad"
  ping 8.8.8.8 || echo "bad"
The same line route and ping
  route; ping 8.8.8.8
List all the existing users /etc/passwd. Display only the names
  cat /etc/passwd | awk -F: '{print $1}'
Create user
  adduser adam
Create group
  addgroup admins
Assign user to the group
  gpasswd -a adam admins
Change the password
  passwd adam
Remove user from the group
  gpasswd -d adam admins
Connect to user
  su user
  
